<TEXT>
in what would be a major victory for 
sudanese rebels leaders said they captured the town of melut 
defeated its army garrison and controlled traffic on the white nile 
river between two major towns 
the capture would mark one of the sudan peoples liberation 
armys northernmost advances in more than seven years of civil war 
the sudanese government has made no mention of fighting in 
melut 350 miles south of the capital of khartoum there was no 
independent confirmation of the report 
in a clandestine radio broadcast monitored in nairobi the rebel 
movement said it overran melut on thursday in an assault that began 
the day before 
the garrison has been wiped out and remnants are being mopped 
up the broadcast said 
it said the citys capture is important to us because we now 
control river transportation between the towns of renk and 
malakal 
melut is roughly 100 miles from both malakal to the south and 
renk to the north 
the mainly christian and animist rebels launched their rebellion 
in early 1983 demanding greater autonomy and economic reforms in 
the three southern provinces of bahr elghazal upper nile and 
equatoria the rebels claim discrimination by the government 
dominated by moslems from the north 
</TEXT>
