<TEXT>
a boeing 767 jet outfitted with a star wars 
sensor designed to scan large areas of space and simultaneously 
track hundreds of targets took its first test flight friday 
the modified 767 carried the worlds most sophisticated 
longwave infrared sensor on a sixhour test flight about 45000 
feet above several western states 
a crew of 17 boeing and hughes aircraft co personnel checked 
how inflight vibration and sound will affect the sensor contained 
in an 86footlong cupola over the front half of the plane 
three months of flight testing over the continental united 
states will be followed by tests using air force targets at 
kwajalein atoll in the pacific ocean 
the project called the airborne optical adjunctairborne 
surveillance testbed is to determine if longwave infrared sensors 
can provide early warning and tracking of enemy ballistic missile 
warheads by sorting them from decoys and debris 
the program is intended to test sensor technology rather than 
develop a prototype for an operational system 
it is managed by the us army strategic defense command for the 
strategic defense initiative or star wars 
the program has already cost 600 million and will reach 700 
million if it continues as planned until 1992 col gary stewart of 
the army strategic defense command in huntsville ala said 
thursday 
steward said the program is two years behind schedule and well 
above original cost estimates of 450 million to 500 million 
</TEXT>
