<TEXT>
a man identified on an immigration computer list 
as a former nazi ss officer was charged in federal court friday 
with failing to disclose his nazi past when applying for a us 
visa 
joseph aloysius goertz 76 traveling on a visa issued in 
stuttgart west germany was ordered held without bail following 
arraignment before us magistrate bert s tokairin who scheduled 
a detention hearing for tuesday 
goertz is in the custody of us immigration and naturalization 
service officials and will be given a medical examination after 
complaining of a heart condition said assistant us attorney 
michael burke 
it was not known how goertz managed to get a visa without 
disclosing his nazi affiliation said oscar villa an ins inspector 
goertz was arrested by immigration officers tuesday after 
arriving at honolulu international airport on a flight from new 
zealand officials said 
his nazi affiliation was discovered when his name came up on an 
ins computer that lists past and present members of the nazi party 
burke said 
goertz told immigration inspectors he had been forced to join 
the ss at the end of 1943 and remained a member until the end of 
world war ii in may 1945 officials said 
however a check of documents captured by us forces in 1945 
showed goertz had been a member since he was 18 years old joining 
the party in 1932 and was an ss storm trooper until 1934 
according to the us justice departments office of special 
investigation osi 
goertz then joined the ss political branch and in 1935 joined 
the intelligence unit according to the osi 
osi believes that this group dealt with spying for the ss 
leadership on opponents of the regime that is jews gypsies 
and others villa said in court documents 
former or current affiliation with the nazi party makes a 
foreigner ineligible for a us visa without a special waiver 
burke said 
</TEXT>
