<TEXT>
the bush administration is resisting soviet 
offers to cut tactical nuclear weapons at sea but the navys top 
admiral says such negotiations might be useful if the soviets 
accepted certain preconditions 
the united states has long opposed arms control measures that 
would limit the number of navy ships or tactical weapons and adm 
carlisle ah trost soon to retire as chief of naval operations 
told congress on friday he saw little prospect for change 
yet trost said that under certain circumstances it might benefit 
the united states to negotiate the elimination of shortrange naval 
nuclear arms arms in this category include antiship missiles 
depth bombs and torpedoes 
yes it could be in our interests if the soviets were 
willing to also eliminate sea and landbased aircraft assigned to 
their naval fleets and if adequate measures were taken to guard 
against cheating trost told the senate armed services subcommittee 
on projection forces 
but ronald lehman director of the arms control and disarmament 
agency testified that the administration is unwilling to consider 
entering into negotiations on tactical nuclear weapons at sea he 
said it was doubtful that any such accord could include 
satisfactory verification measures 
weve come to the conclusion that now is not the time to 
address the issue he said 
the top arms adviser to soviet president mikhail s gorbachev 
marshal sergei akhromeyev told the same subcommittee on tuesday 
that future talks on other categories of nuclear and conventional 
weapons could be derailed by continued us resistance to naval 
arms talks 
lehman said that in current arms negotiations the soviets had 
not formally insisted on linking any agreements to future 
discussions about naval nuclear arms 
gorbachev proposed at his last meeting with president bush in 
malta last december that the superpowers undertake to negotiate 
cuts in shortrange naval nuclear arms but the administration has 
resisted 
the united states has about 2200 tactical nuclear weapons at 
sea compared with about 2700 for the soviets according to 
figures supplied by the subcommittee 
lehman said the elimination of tactical naval nuclear arms would 
undermine the united states traditional position as the 
predominant naval force in the world and it could hurt the 
security of us allies who depend on us naval power 
trost while expressing similar doubts suggested that such 
talks might be acceptable 
if we could with proper confidence in their willingness to 
abide by an agreement be sure there were no nuclear weapons that 
threatened either sides ships at sea im sure wed both be more 
comfortable that way he said 
later under questioning trost said he was referring only to 
the tactical category of naval weapons not to seabased cruise or 
ballistic missiles of longer range 
yes it could be in our interests if all the ifs i 
previously stated are included he said and you could label me 
as a lifetime pessimist on the likelihood of ever concluding such 
an agreement he added quickly 
trosts description of an acceptable formula for negotiations to 
eliminate shortrange nuclear arms at sea appeared similar to that 
offered tuesday by akhromeyev who said his government was willing 
to include related weaponry such as that carried on aircraft 
carriers submarines and landbased naval aircraft 
</TEXT>
