<TEXT>
president bushs open skies proposal to 
lessen eastwest tensions through aerial surveillance is snagged in 
negotiations and the state department is blaming the soviet union 
for the setback 
in a statement friday that confirmed reports from budapest the 
site of the treaty talks the department said several key issues 
were in dispute 
these include the territory to be overflown by unarmed aircraft 
and the number of such surveillance flights 
today was the tentative deadline for signing the treaty 
at least two other prospective eastwest accords also are in 
trouble 
treaties to curb us and soviet longrange nuclear missiles and 
to set lower troops ceilings in europe have not been completed 
negotiators are unable to settle their differences even under the 
pressure of an approaching ussoviet summit 
secretary of state james a baker iii is flying to moscow on 
sunday night to try to overcome the impasse 
richard boucher a department spokesman said the soviets had 
blocked agreement on most of the open skies issues because they 
favor a less intrusive regime 
last year when bush reworked a proposal first made more than 30 
years ago by president eisenhower open skies was promoted as a 
us contribution to ease eastwest tensions 
bush was signaling his determination to match soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev in overcoming cold war suspicions 
last december in brussels the 16 north atlantic treaty 
organization allies approved bushs proposal to let unarmed warsaw 
pact aircraft fly over their territory in search of military 
activity 
then in february nato and warsaw pact countries meeting in 
ottawa canada agreed to set annual quotas for overflights and to 
invite neutral nations to participate details were to be settled 
in time for a treaty signing today 
but the negotiations did not as we had hoped they would 
reach agreement on an open skies treaty boucher said 
despite some progress key issues remain to be decided he 
said 
among them were what sort of sensors would be permitted on the 
overflying aircraft and the territory to be covered 
the soviets wanted to include nonparticipating countries in the 
surveillance plan there also was disagreement over how much 
information would be shared between the two sides 
the delay in concluding an open skies treaty is part of a 
general slowdown on the arms control front 
negotiations in vienna to reduce troops tanks and other 
nonnuclear weapons in europe have stalled over aircraft 
helicopters and a system to verify compliance 
meanwhile the united states and the soviet union are having 
problems in geneva trying to complete a treaty to reduce their 
longrange nuclear missiles bombers and submarines 
baker hopes to reach an agreement in principle next week with 
soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze for bush and 
gorbachev to sign during their may 30june 3 washington summit 
most observers rate his chances as poor 
the talks scheduled for wednesday through friday in moscow 
have already been extended to saturday a sign of the workload 
facing baker and shevardnadze 
however ronald lehman director of the arms control and 
disarmament agency told a senate armed services subcommittee 
friday we see no reason why we shouldnt be able to get an 
agreement at the talks 
the nato allies saw an open skies treaty as a way to ensure 
compliance with a troopreduction accord each participating 
country would have to permit at least one surveillance flight every 
three months 
the united states the soviet union canada and the european 
nations would participate 
</TEXT>
