<TEXT>
conservation groups say interior secretary 
manuel lujans call for reexamining protection of endangered 
species is outrageous and recalls the reagan administrations 
prodevelopment policies toward the environment 
lujan sparked the criticism friday after he was quoted as saying 
that congress should look at the federal law protecting endangered 
species with an eye toward increasing its flexibility 
lujan cited as one example of how the endangered species act 
causes problems the controversy in arizona over construction of a 
200 million telescope on a mountain inhabited by rare and 
endangered red squirrels 
do we have to save every subspecies lujan suggested in an 
interview thursday with the denver post the red squirrel is the 
best example nobodys told me the difference between a red 
squirrel a black one or a brown one 
he said federal law protecting endangered species was just too 
tough and added weve got to change it 
in interviews with two other colorado newspapers lujan vowed to 
find a way to build the animaslaplata water project in the state 
although its construction has been threatened by the endangered 
squawfish he said one option might be to move the fish elsewhere 
as word of lujans comments circulated friday conservationists 
reacted angrily 
michael francis of the wilderness society said the remarks 
showed mr lujans incredible lack of understanding of biology 
and public policy 
id have to say hes getting pretty close to another jim watt 
mr lujan certainly is trying to better his mark said 
francis referring to the reagan administration interior secretary 
who was widely criticized by environmentalists for his 
prodevelopment views 
jay hair president of the national wildlife federation said he 
was incensed that the very cabinet official whose job it is to be 
the countrys frontline protector of endangered wildlife would 
make such outrageous statements 
hair said the mount graham red squirrel the focus of attention 
in the arizona telescope dispute case is in the 11th hour of 
existence on the planet fewer than 200 of the squirrels are left 
lujans press secretary steve goldstein did not dispute the 
quotes as reported he said his boss had sought only to point out 
some frustrations he has had with enforcing the endangered 
species act 
goldstein said lujan wants congress to reexamine when 
subspecies should be protected under the federal law and what 
protection should be afford when the same species exist in multiple 
locations he said lujan does not believe those issues will weaken 
the law 
conservationists and some members of congress however 
interpreted lujans comments as a clear attempt to weaken the law 
congress will strongly resist any attempt to weaken the 
endangered species act sen john chafee rri said in a 
statement 
while lujan a former republican congressman from new mexico 
has said he is concerned about aspects of the federal law he 
promised to continue to enforce its provisions 
