<TEXT>
pope john paul ii concerned by the 
growth of usbased evangelical protestant churches in mexico 
pleaded with converts to return to the roman catholic faith that 
shaped this countrys modern history 
the church awaits you with open arms to bring you back 
together with christ john paul said friday speaking to a 
joyful flagwaving crowd that topped 200000 he spoke from an 
altar atop a pyramid that resembled a mayan temple 
the pontiff was on the sixth day of an eightday visit to 
mexico today he visits the provincial city of zacatecas before 
returning to mexico city to address a gathering of intellectuals 
the popes homilies here and in tuxtla gutierrez 90 miles to 
the south were directed to mexicos indians and reflected growing 
alarm in the vatican over the success of noncatholic churches in 
latin america particularly in mexico 
protestant evangelical activity has been strongest in the 
southeastern states of tabasco chiapas and oaxaca as well as 
across the border in guatemala protestants have translated the 
bible into indian tongues for the first time and found a receptive 
audience among landless peasants and poor forced to migrate to 
cities 
villahermosa is the capital of tabasco where an estimated 20 
percent of the states 14 million residents are noncatholic 
twice the national average 
i think again about those people who have distanced themselves 
from the catholic church i would like to meet with each one of 
you to say return to the breast of the church your mother the 
pope cried in his homily 
in tuxtla gutierrez the pope urged mexicos downtrodden indians 
to fight to improve their lives 
dont be seduced by vices like alcohol abuse which causes so 
many ravages and dont cooperate with drug trafficking which 
causes destruction to so many people in the world the pope told 
a crowd of more than 150000 in a field below chiapas misty green 
mountains 
the pope encouraged indians not to lose hope in the face of 
poverty or the continuous assalt on your cultural traditions he 
praised the traditional indian emphasis on the paradise of the 
afterlife but you also have the obligation to improve your own 
human situation 
john paul also expressed concern for refugees fleeing political 
persecution and death squads in guatemala which borders chiapas 
and tabasco 
the southeastern trips main aim however was shoring up the 
local catholic church in the face of competition the churches 
growing fastest in mexico include baptists jehovahs witnesses 
pentecostalists assembly of god and mormons 
those who convert are often disenchanted with a political and 
economic system that is destroying native culture and spreading 
poverty and discrimination despite reform laws many have lost 
their communal lands to private farmers 
the pontiff wearing gold and red robes said some people may 
have turned to the evangelical churches because they felt more 
welcome in a small group among familiar people who help each 
other 
others he said may have left the catholic church because of 
material worries an apparent reference to usbased churches 
that distribute aid among the mexican poor although most 
proselytizing is now carried out by mexican converts 
in tuxtla gutierrez john paul addressed the crowd briefly in 
two indian tongues tzotzil and zoque drawing laughter when he 
joked about his pronunciation in villahermosa the pontiff tried 
out chontal and cholco 
over six million of mexicos 85 million citizens do not 
understand spanish speaking only mayan dialects or other indian 
tongues 
before the service in tuxtla gutierrez john paul prayed at the 
cathedral and comforted the families of 28 pilgrims who died 
thursday in a plane crash while flying in to see the pope 
death is not the last word because for those who have faith 
life does not end it transforms itself the pope said he kissed 
a cross on the coffin of luis miguel canton marin the bishop of 
tapachula who had worked closely with indian groups 
