<TEXT>
once again students rioting in the 
streets and angry workers jabbing fists in the air have marred 
south koreas public image and alarmed the government 
for years south korea has been working hard to build an image 
for itself as a safe stable place to visit and invest its 
economic boom has bolstered the picture of a strong industrious 
nation 
yet the south korean governments popularity is at an alltime 
low and its exportfueled economy has sagged inflation is running 
in double digits and the volatile stock market hit a twoyear low 
foreign investors have besieged consultants embassies trade 
offices and government ministries seeking assurances of the 
nations stability 
the latest wave of unrest has been sparked by workers who are 
demanding more rights and more say in management and radical 
students who blame the government for a variety of troubles 
in timehonored korean fashion complaints are registered with 
protests which often turn violent 
though the latest demonstrations have been far smaller than 
those three years ago that forced electoral reforms the government 
is cracking down hard to save itself as well as its international 
image 
on wednesday about 100000 students hurling firebombs and rocks 
fought police in 17 cities the largest antigovernment protests 
since 1987 
two weeks ago tens of thousands of workers walked off their 
jobs in sympathy after riot police charged into the nations 
largest shipyard and the staterun television network to end 
strikes 
so far this year students and workers have not joined together 
but history suggests that an alliance of the two groups can have 
grave results for governments 
in 1987 protests by students and workers combined to force the 
government to accept reforms that eventually led to popular 
elections for the presidency and the victory of roh taewoo 
in putting down this years worker unrest rohs government 
gambled that the labor turmoil would not become a wider political 
issue wages have risen 50 to 60 percent in the last two years and 
labor rights not economics were the workers concern 
most workers returned to their jobs this week but the 
governments heavyhandedness in dealing with the workers angered 
radical students who have been accusing the roh government for 
months of being antireform and dictatorial 
students dissidents and opposition politicians are also upset 
about the merging of the ruling party with two opposition parties 
earlier this year which gave the government overwhelming control 
of the national assembly 
roh said the merger was needed for political and economic 
stability because parliamentary deadlocks had bogged down affairs 
of state 
kim daejung leader of the opposition party for peace and 
democracy said this week it was time for roh to completely 
revamp his thinking about everything in this country 
kim said roh should disband the new party call new elections 
and realize that labor and business problems cannot be solved with 
a naked fist 
rohs problems are reflected in a poll taken by his ruling 
democratic liberal party that indicated 88 percent of the voters 
dont like the way things are going rohs popularity is at 12 
percent his lowest ever the party said 
but roh said this week that things arent so bad 
the real problem is that a pervasive sense of anxiety is 
making the situation more troublesome than it actually is roh 
told a nationwide television audience 
he acknowledged the economy was in trouble but said it was 
recovering he admitted prices were up but said inflation would 
level off 
several cabinet ministers held an unusual nationwide television 
news conference aimed at showing government resolve to deal firmly 
with violent protests 
prosecutors said student leaders and dissidents who incited 
violence would be rounded up 
the nations newspapers for their part suggest that its time 
for both the demonstrators and the government to shape up 
the performance of the roh administration has not been very 
satisfactory said the donga ilbo newspaper to the protesters 
it advised we must achieve solid democratic reforms only through 
legal methods even if this may be rather timeconsuming 
