director nils gaup made his first film 
based on a 1000yearold legend he heard from his grandfather in 
the hopes it would be a hit among his native lapp people 
it was then the film called pathfinder was nominated for 
an oscar as best foreign film and won rave reviews in london and 
at numerous film festivals on friday it opened in new york 
the film is in lapp a language spoken by less than 40000 
traditional reindeer herders in the northern fringes of scandianvia 
and the soviet union 
i made it for a lapp audience so when it was successful 
elsewhere it was a big surprise to me said gaup 35 back in 
oslo after a trip to new york to help promote the film 
pathfinder is based on the legend of a lapp boy who saved 
his people from a band of barbarians that had killed his family 
it was filmed on the tundra in northern norway near gaups home 
village of kautokeino in keeping with the legend it was filmed in 
the depths of artic winter with temperatures plummeting to minus 
40 
professional and amateur lapp actors from norway sweden and 
finland took part in the eightweek filming it took at least as 
long to make the reindeerskin clothing and the tents the film 
cost 23 million part of which came from a norwegian government 
grant 
sitting at a sidewalk cafe in oslo gaup said he was not 
concerned about how new york critics would react to the film 
what they say doesnt really mean anything to me because the 
film has already done so much more than i ever hoped for he said 
he said he intends to write and direct other lapp films to help 
preserve his culture 
he recalled his boyhood in arctic norway when lapps swapped 
tales and used reindeer for transportation 
the intrusion of television and other modern conveniences has 
begun to change that now snowmobiles are as common as sleds and 
people have stopped sitting around telling legends he said 
thats why it is so important to tell these stories the lapp 
culture is one of the last left with direct ties to ancient ways of 
thinking 
