federal health officials are recommending that 
physicians use a recently approved drug as standard treatment for 
recurrences of a lifethreatening infection in aids patients 
the drug fluconazole has proven so successful that a 
governmentsponsored comparative study has been stopped and the 
drug offered to all participants officials at the national 
institute of allergy and infectious diseases said friday 
in the study fluconazole was compared with amphotericin b 
which has been the standard treatment for the infection as well as 
for recurrences 
the infection cryptococcal meningitis affects the brain and 
nervous system about 10 percent of aids victims get the disease 
and after treatment for the initial infection they need lifetime 
maintenance therapy to prevent recurrence 
the study was stopped april 30 and preliminary results were 
distributed to physicians who treat patients with aids officials 
said 
patients in the study had been treated successfully with 
amphotericin b when they first got the infection of the 106 
patients who received fluconazole to prevent recurrence two had 
relapses of the 77 who received amphotericin b 13 got the 
infection again niaid said 
fluconazole made by pfizer inc has fewer side effects than 
amphotericin b also fluconazole can be given by mouth while 
amphotericin b must be given intravenously 
amphotericin b causes nausea fever and can impair kidney and 
bone marrow function fluconazole has few side effects but in some 
patients it can cause abdominal discomfort nausea skin rash and 
sometimes liver damage 
