a top iranian official called for the 
release of western hostages in lebanon and said washington could 
show good will by releasing billions of dollars in iranian assets 
a newspaper reported today 
the tehran times quoted hussein musavian directorgeneral of 
irans foreign ministry as saying the recent release of two 
americans held in lebanon was due to his countrys efforts 
we believe that all countries especially those that have 
influence in lebanon should exert their maximum efforts for the 
release of the hostages he said 
the criteria for these efforts should be to release all 
hostages regardless of their nationality solely for humanitarian 
causes and without an preconditions or deals 
it was the latest in a series of conflicting statements by 
iranian officials on the 16 western hostages in lebanon most of 
whom are held by proiranian shiite moslem groups 
the government of president hashemi rafsanjani has pressed for 
freedom for the captives as a way to improve relations with the 
west to thereby get help rebuilding irans economy 
but radicals argue that holding the hostages is a means of 
confronting the west which they view as evil and working against 
the interests of iran 
after the april release of americans robert polhill 55 and 
frank reed 57 iran and the hostageholders demanded a goodwill 
gesture from the united states before further releases 
president bush has thanked iran and syria for their efforts in 
securing the releases but has refused to negotiate for hostages 
musavian said that as long as the united states continues its 
hostile and negative attitude toward iran relations between 
the countries will not improve 
their hands are free for taking positive practical steps such 
as the release of iranian assets frozen by them for years he was 
quoted as saying in an interview in vienna with austrian 
journalists 
the united states and iran agreed wednesday on settling about 
3200 claims together worth about 50 million filed against the 
iranian government by us citizens who were in iran during the 
islamic revolution in 1979 
most of the claims involve loss of personal property and their 
settlement was believed to be a step toward settling a 
multibilliondollar dispute that began in 1979 after washington 
froze iranian assets 
iran says the assets amount to 11 billion but the united 
states says the figure is exaggerated 
the western hostages in lebanon include six americans four 
britons two germans two swiss an italian and an irishman 
