an explosion rocked a panamanian tanker drydocked 
in the houston ship channel setting the ship ablaze and injuring 
at least three crew members before the fire was extinguished this 
morning authorities said 
authorities closed the channel after the fire aboard the seta 
was reported about 6 pm friday to keep flames from spreading to 
other ships but the blaze was extinguished about 12 hours later 
and ship channel officials allowed oneway traffic around the 
drydocked tanker 
all the significant fires are out on the tanker but we are 
posting a reflash watch where firefighters make sure there are no 
hot spots that might catch fire again said coast guard lt mary 
landry 
houston firefighters working from fireboats in the channel had 
battled the threealarm blaze through the night at least three 
firefighters who entered the burning ship were treated for heat 
exhaustion 
no deaths were reported aboard the 374foot tanker and 
authorities believed most of its 20 to 25 crew members were 
accounted for but firefighters had been unable by early today to 
enter the lowest compartments of the ship to determine whether all 
had escaped 
the flames apparently were confined to the ships crew quarters 
and had not spread to the cargo hold which contained residues of 
four explosive chemicals methane acetone kerosene and hexane 
said fire department spokesman joe phillips 
none of the tanks are on fire coast guard lt robert said 
late friday but thats a concern of ours theres some very 
flammable gas in those tanks it is possible there could be 
explosions so were spraying a lot of water on them to keep them 
cool 
the injured crew members suffered burns said dr paul pepe 
head of houstons emergency medical services two were in good 
condition and one in fair condition early today 
the coast guard was investigating a report that combustible 
acetone spilled into the channel from the seta or another ship and 
ignited triggering the explosion 
we had just finished eating dinner when we heard an explosion 
i just jumped off into the water i dont know where it came 
from said mandic dusko a yugoslavian electrician on the seta 
i was sitting here in my camper eating supper and it sounded 
like when a big heavy slab of steel drops like a crane falling 
said alabama brown 43 a houston ship repair co welder working 
nearby i looked out and saw yellow flames about as high as that 
yellow crane over there it just kind of shook the place 
the seta was in drydock to be cleaned officials said 
