floodwaters that wreaked havoc in texas arkansas 
and oklahoma swelled into louisiana today and forecasters said 
residents in lowlying areas were not out of danger 
intermittent rains fell friday in the region and were forecast 
for the next few days 
the crest of the trinity river which soaked north texas after 
heavy rains a week ago headed for the gulf coast and authorities 
warned residents northeast of houston to expect more flooding by 
next week 
about 7000 lowland residents downstream of lake livingston dam 
60 miles northeast of houston were told to evacuate their 
subdivisions three subdivisions in liberty county remained cut off 
from main roads by rising water said jim mitchum the countys 
emergency management coordinator 
however many homes in the area sit on ninefoot stilts and 
most people are riding it out he said 
among the dangers of staying put are butane and propane tanks 
floating downstream and smashing into homes and fire ants by the 
pound floating on debris into homes along with racoons and 
snakes he said 
snakes and fire ants like to ride out the floods too 
mitchum said and theres nothing like seeing fire ants piled a 
foot high coming right at you 
the army corps of engineers said the volume of water expected to 
move through northwestern louisiana as the red river drains along 
the texasoklahoma border and through arkansas would exceed the 
record floods of 1927 and 1957 but that levees and other flood 
control systems built since then would prevent a flood disaster 
however about 20 people evacuated from a trailer park friday as 
the red attacked levees near shreveports downtown airport 
in natchitoches parish la contractors were building a ring 
levee on bayou poisson five miles east of natchitoches to keep 
the red from backing up into the cane river and flooding parts of 
the city 
elsewhere in the parish in the vick community about 50 
farmers using bulldozers tractors and plows worked to build up 
an earthen levee to keep the water from flooding all their fields 
the corps of engineers said the makeshift levee was three to 
five miles long friday thats a major undertaking to build 
something that long that fast said michael logue chief of 
public relations for the corps vicksburg miss district 
along the oklahoma border nearly 200 national guardsmen 
continued working around the clock to reinforce levees in the 
