<TEXT>
move still stands for fear on philadelphias 
osage avenue a street of row houses sprayed with bullets five 
years ago and then destroyed by fire as police tried to rid the 
neighborhood of the radical group 
the city has rebuilt the 61 homes that burned down by a fire 
that started when police dropped a bomb on a house occupied by 
heavily armed move members on may 13 1985 an adult and a child 
escaped the house eleven others including five children and 
founder john africa died 
but residents are afraid move will resurface 
police detective edward tenuto said saturday that police dont 
know how many move members there are in the city fifteen are in 
jail one is the adult survivor of the bombing and the rest were 
convicted on unrelated charges 
along with fear the residents are puzzled that no city or 
police officials were charged in the incident sen arlen specter 
tried unsuccessfully last week to get a federal grand jury to 
reopen the case before the statute of limitations on civil rights 
violations expired at midnight saturday 
a memorial service was held friday night for the victims and 
panel discussions and workshops on public policy and human 
relations were running all day saturday 
gerald renfrow who lives across the street from where the move 
house once stood serves as spokesman for his neighbors on osage 
avenue who are afraid to talk to reporters 
im the block captain here ill answer your questions said 
renfrow 
although some considered leaving this workingclass neighborhood 
after the fire destroyed their homes the majority of the estimated 
270 displaced residents eventually moved into the 130000plus 
homes rebuilt by the city 
but nobody has moved into the new home built where the move 
house once stood it is empty guarded by police around the clock 
steel bars protecting its windows and doors 
louise james a move sympathizer who owned the original house 
has fought the city for the new dwelling 
the city gave her 2280 in 1987 saying that was what the 
property was worth when it was condemned in 1988 she sued the 
city claiming title to the new house and 375000 in damages but 
a federal judge dismissed it saying the statute of limitations for 
such a suit had expired 
on several occasions ms james the sister of move founder john 
