foreign students applying to us universities some schools in 
canada and europe also ask for the test scores to measure a foreign 
students proficiency in english 
students say that since last years military crackdown on the 
prodemocracy movement most are studying english in the hopes of 
going overseas 
but apparently not all are confident enough to take the test 
yet chinese officials say the number of testtakers has not 
increased noticeably 
about 400 students took the exam saturday at the beijing foreign 
languages institute 
im so testedout im dizzy said one 20yearold man as he 
left the exam room 
the 2hour exam tests writing ability reading and listening 
comprehension and grammar out of a possible 800 points most 
american universities want a 575point minimum for admission and a 
higher score for a scholarship 
the exam was first administered in china in 1981 to just 600 
people at three test sites it now is given four times a year last 
year about 40000 chinese took the test 
students pay the equivalent of a months salary to take the exam 
and of those who can pay not everyone can take the exam last 
year china began requiring a letter of approval from each persons 
work unit or univeristy communist party secretary before 
registering for the test 
students at some test centers have complained of rampant 
cheating ignored by proctors who sympathize with the students 
desire to leave china and want to help them out 
but both the educational testing service in princeton nj 
which administers the exam and the china international 
examinations coordination bureau which supervises the test in 
china say cheating is not a problem 
the us embassy in beijing says last year it granted 6301 
study visas 
china has said it will send 3000 students abroad in 1990 but 
has placed new restrictions on studying at foreign universities 
they include requiring students without scholarships to work five 
years before going overseas 
the measures were apparently prompted by fears students would 
not return especially after the june 1989 military crackdown on 
student protesters in which hundreds perhaps thousands died 
authorities are clearly concerned about students being exposed 
abroad to ideas and lifestyles that might make them rebellious or 
inclined not to return 
in the past 12 years china has sent between 60000 and 80000 
students to foreign countries but nearly half have failed to 
return more than 20000 chinese students have gone overseas on 
their own and many stayed abroad 
