a measure that would impose stiff fines or jail 
sentences for insulting or slandering the soviet president was 
approved saturday by one chamber of the soviet legislature but 
failed in the other chamber tass said the bill will now go to a 
committee to be reworked and introduced at another session the 
official soviet news agency reported 
the measure was introduced after an angry red square protest may 
1 in which thousands of people shouted or displayed slogans 
demanding the leadership resign some called president mikhail s 
gorbachev a dictator 
alexander n yakovlev a close adviser to gorbachev said the 
demonstrators had insulted kremlin leaders who left their 
reviewing stand atop lenins mausoleum after enduring about 20 
minutes of the protest 
the legislation appeared to have been brought up for debate 
hastily but it was not immediately clear whether it was directly 
connected to the protest 
there previously had been no reports that such a draft measure 
existed and as late as thursday legislative officials made no 
mention of it on the agenda 
tass said the bill to protect the honor and dignity of the 
soviet president was approved by the council of the union one 
chamber of the legislature but it failed in the other house the 
council of the nationalities 
speakers who favored the law said statements discrediting or 
insulting the head of state can help destabilize society the news 
agency said other deputies insisted that the bill contain a 
clearcut definition of what constitutes an insult 
yevgeny sorokin a spokesman for the supreme soviet or 
legislature said the bill would impose a fine of up to 5000 two 
years in a labor camp or three years in jail for slandering or 
insulting the president 
tass quoted yuri kalmykov chairman of the parliamentary 
legislation committee as saying the measure was necessary because 
the head of state needed special protection 
the bill would cover all public pronouncements containing 
critical remarks concerning the activity of the soviet president or 
a policy pursued under his leadership tass said 
under the measure an offense conducted with the help of the 
news media could be punishable by a jail term of up to six years 
tass said it said a newspaper radio or tv station carrying such 
material could be fined up to 41600 and be suspended from 
broadcasting or publishing 
the soviet parliament elected gorbachev to a new powerful 
executive presidency on march 15 
gorbachev has said he wants to use the presidency to unite the 
country but criticism of his policies and pressure from some 
republics for autonomy or outright secession have become more acute 
since gorbachev took the new post 
