<TEXT>
mexicos congress on saturday approved a 
constitutional amendment to allow complete private ownership of 
banks eight years after they were nationalized 
the measure now needs the approval of the senate and 31 state 
legislatures 
the 33954 vote came eight hours after the chamber of deputies 
convened early saturday to take up the issue there were 12 
abstentions 
passage was virtually assured after the conservative national 
action party threw its support behind the amendment 
the measure was proposed a week earlier by president carlos 
salinas de gortari and supported by his institutional revolutionary 
party 
members of leftist parties could not gather enough votes to 
block the reform which needed a twothirds vote to pass the 
governing party and the conservatives together have 364 of the 500 
congressional seats 
the measure goes next to the senate where the governing party 
has an overwhelming majority a simple majority also is needed in 
31 state legislatures 
banks were nationalized in 1982 by outgoing president jose lopez 
portillo following an economic downturn attributed to a fall in 
price for oil mexicos leading export 
lopez portillos successor miguel de la madrid amended the 
legislation to allow up to 34 percent private investment in banks 
under the proposal passed saturday commerical banks could be 
100 percent privately owned but some specialized development banks 
would remain in government hands 
other details of the privatization remained to be worked out 
</TEXT>
