<TEXT>
indian leaders from five south american 
nations returned to their rain forest homelands saturday after 
forming an alliance with international environmentalists to 
cooperate to save the amazon jungle 
thirteen leaders of 12 million indians living in the amazon 
river basin in colombia ecuador peru bolivia and brazil signed 
a pact late friday night with representatives of 14 international 
conservationist groups 
the agreement came after three days of meetings in this isolated 
amazon river port 715 miles northeast of lima 
the indians convened the gathering to demand a voice in 
environmentists efforts to preserve the vast amazon jungle from 
destruction 
many times conservationists see only the pretty birds the 
pretty rivers the pretty green trees evaristo nugkuag an 
aguaruna indian leader from peru said in the closing ceremony 
you forget that indians live in this jungle that we are its true 
caretakers its true protectors 
nugkuag is president of the coordinating body for indigenous 
peoples organizations of the amazon basin 
the agreement was signed by representatives of such 
organizations as greenpeace and the world wildlife fund it said 
the group recognized the importance of the indians own proposals 
for conservation of the amazon 
an estimated 50 to 100 acres of tropical rain forest is being 
cleared in the amazon every minute according to ecologists for the 
smithsonian institution 
the indians are battling to save their homelands from migrant 
farmers ranchers loggers gold prospectors oil companies and 
other groups seeking economic gain from the jungle 
lately they have also become concerned about the hundreds of 
thousands of acres of forest being destroyed to grow coca leaves 
the raw material for cocaine 
in their first meeting with environmentalists in washington in 
october they expressed growing doubts about the debtfornature 
swaps in which some of the foreign debt crippling south american 
countries is traded for a commitment to set aside rain forest lands 
as wilderness preserves 
without consulting us you have traded our land for a debt we 
did not incur nugkuag told the washington gathering 
in such arrangements conservation groups assume a portion of a 
countrys debt to foreign banks in exchange for the countrys 
setting aside land for protection 
since 1987 in latin america there have been debtfornature 
swaps in bolivia ecuador and costa rica 
the indians complain that the swaps have shown disregard for 
their rights they propose that indian tribes be given stewardship 
of their ancestral territories as part of the swaps 
no accord was reached in iquitos on the debtswap issue but the 
indian leaders and conservationists agreed to meet again in 
washington in september to pursue joint actions 
barbara bramble the head of the national wildlife federations 
international program said the environmentalists realized the 
indians are important allies in the fight to save the amazon 
were an organization dedicated to the wise use of 
resources she said the people who are doing that best are 
tribal people not north americans 
</TEXT>
