coast guard approval of exxon corps 
final plan for cleaning up the valdez oil spill includes a 
requirement that the company protect sites that may have been 
inhabited 7000 years ago 
the work plan for exxons final cleanup was approved friday by 
coast guard rear adm david ciancaglini 
the approval requires that exxon develop a program to protect 
cultural resources such as archaeological artifacts in areas 
affected by the march 1989 spill of nearly 11 million gallons of 
crude oil in prince william sound 
exxon already had been working on plans to protect cultural and 
archaeological resources before ciancaglini made it a provision of 
his approval said company spokesman joe tucker 
the admiral just wanted it in writing agreed coast guard 
spokeswoman gail williams were talking the same program but we 
just want to make sure its done 
three teams of archaeologists in helicopters have been surveying 
prince william sound and the gulf of alaska charles mobley an 
anchorage archaeologist overseeing those aspects of the cleanup for 
exxon said saturday 
mobley said the best way to protect the areas cultural 
resources would be to stay clear of it altogether even after the 
spill 
second best would be stationing archaeologists to watch over 
exxon crews cleaning up beaches as was done last year he said 
exxon federal and state land managers and representatives of 
alaska native corporations are working to reach agreement on how 
best to preserve the archeologically important sites to satisfy the 
coast guard 
the entire oil spill area has archaeology in it mobley said 
he said the area reaching west from prince william sound and 
south to the alaska peninsula represents 7000 years of habitation 
by natives 
authorities say lack of research funds has left the region 
largely unexplored 
but mobley said one spinoff of the attempt to protect 
archaeological artifacts has been an increase in archeological 
knowledge 
before the oil spill archaeology program there were maybe 300 
known sites of archeological importance in the region mobley 
said weve more than doubled that now including sites of 
historic interest 
the tanker exxon valdez wrecked on a chartered reef on march 24 
1989 spewing north slope crude in the nations largest oil spill 
the spill coated hundreds of miles of shoreline and killed hundreds 
of otters and thousands of birds and other animals 
the tankers skipper joseph hazelwood was convicted in march 
of a misdemeanor charge of negligent discharge of oil into state 
waters but was acquitted of more serious charges 
exxon and its exxon shipping co are charged with two federal 
felonies and two misdemeanors in the spill the trial in anchorage 
on charges that include allowing an incompetent crew to operate the 
exxon valdez was postponed indefinitely last sunday 
