<TEXT>
car bombs on saturday ripped through two 
malls packed with lastminute mothers day shoppers killing at 
least 19 people and injuring 143 the health ministry said 
late saturday another car bomb exploded outside a crowded 
restaurant in the southern city of cali killing six people and 
wounding at least 20 the caracol radio network reported it gave 
no further details 
no one claimed immediate responsibility for any of the bombings 
but the rcn radio network quoted a police colonel as saying 
authorities believed the bombs in the capital were the work of drug 
traffickers the government has blamed the traffickers for dozens 
of bombings that have killed more than 200 people since august 
a health ministry statement said 19 people were killed in the 
bogota bombings and at least 13 of the 143 injured were in critical 
condition in local hospitals 
hundreds of policemen and soldiers swarmed into the area the 
defense ministry in a communique said it had ordered the police 
and soldiers to search for more bombs and to try to find the people 
who set the two bombs 
sirens of ambulances and fire trucks and the screams of people 
could be heard in live radio reports from the scene the injured 
were taken to five hospitals and a red cross station which were 
issuing radio appeals for blood donations 
rcn said the bombs went off within minutes of one another at 
about 415 pm one was set at the niza shopping center in northern 
bogota and the other at the cafam shopping center in the citys 
northwest 
the two shopping centers were packed with people making last 
minute purchases for mothers day on sunday rcn said in a report 
at the cafam shopping center many of the casualties appeared to 
be aboard a crowded bus that was passing by rcn said the radio 
quoted a police explosives expert as saying the bomb was made from 
about 220 pounds of dyanmite 
rcn radio network reported that four children including a 
4yearold boy and a 7yearold girl were among the 13 dead found 
there 
the bomb at the niza shopping center in an upperclass 
neighborhood destroyed at least 41 cars and 200 homes and 
apartments were damaged police col jose camelo said in an 
interview with rcn the radio said 16 stores were damaged by the 
100pound bomb which left a threefootdeep crater 
the niza bomb exploded in a parking lot across from the new 
threelevel mall glass from 20foothigh plateglass windows 
turned to shrapnel the radio report said 
