<TEXT>
results of a government household survey released 
friday suggest the number of dallas county residents infected with 
the aids virus is lower than health officials had estimated 
the random inperson survey last fall which required residents 
to undergo an aids test showed that 04 percent or about 4000 
county residents tested positive for the virus 
the survey first requested by president reagan in 1987 was to 
be a blueprint for a possible national survey of adults carrying 
the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv which causes aids 
after a small survey in pennsylvania the national centers for 
disease control asked dallas county to be the final test for the 
national survey 
previously local and federal health officials had estimated the 
number of people infected with aids in dallas county at 5600 to 
16000 based on trends in aids cases 
taking into account residents excluded from the survey such as 
institutionalized people the number of infected persons is 7500 
at the most officials said the study was conducted on 1446 
composing a representative sample of the countys population 
officials said 
